  "value": "Medium",
  "why": "The paper provides empirical diagnostic insight by linking discovered failures to model internals and statistical failure patterns (neuron/gate activations, coverage increases, temporal activation patterns) and uses these links to explain differences between benign and attacked models and to interpret LSTM behaviour. However, it does not generally trace failures to deeper root causes such as dataset bias, spurious feature reliance, or overfitting across all cases — the analysis is mainly at the level of internal activation/coverage patterns and statistical distributions rather than full causal root-cause attribution.",
  "evidence": "Section IV (page 1194) defines metrics based on internal components: \"we present a family of three coverage metrics (BC, SC, and TC) for the testing of LSTM models. These metrics take into account both the values of structural information ξs,a_t for s ∈ S and a ∈ A ... and their stepwise and bounded-length temporal relations.\" (IV. LSTM TEST COVERAGE METRICS, p.1194).\n\nSection VII-C2 (page 1201) links backdoor behaviour to internal activation/coverage: \"The experimental results describe that backdoor input activate same internal behavior with clean input for a benign classifier. In contrast to this, the backdoor input to malicious classifier will induce different internal activation, which can be seen from the apparent increase of coverage in T+B.\" (VII.C.2 Detecting Backdoor Input in RNNs, p.1201).\n\nSection VII-G (page 1203) uses coverage times to explain LSTM processing patterns (diagnostic interpretation of where the model attends): \"If we combine SC and BC plots, the whole working process of LSTM layer inside the MNIST model becomes transparent. ... At the beginning, the top rows of MNIST images are blank and do not contribute to the model prediction. ... When the input rows containing digits are fed to the LSTM cells, the model will start learning and the short-term memory, represented by the outputs ht, start to have strong reactions.\" (VII.G Exhibition of Internal Working Mechanism, p.1203).\n\nSection VII-E (page 1202) reports statistical failure-pattern differences between attack-based methods and their testing: \"This easily leads to the situation where the generated adversarial samples are concentrated in a 'buggy' area of the input space, as shown in Table IX and Fig. 7.\" (VII.E Comparison With Attack-Based Defect Detection, p.1202).\n\nThese passages show the paper empirically links failures to internal activation/coverage patterns and to statistical distributions of failures, but do not provide broad causal attributions (e.g., dataset bias or spurious-feature reliance) for most failure types."
